»CL1:Wade:»CL0: So, let me get this straight.
      You code only for parties? 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: At this time - yes.

»CL9:<»CL1:Wade sighs disdainfully»CL9:>»

»CL1:Wade:»CL0: It sounds to me as if you are
      driven by profit and gain. Does
this motivate your work? 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: That's true. But this is not the
     only thing that make coders work
harder, the other one is to be a well
known and respected coder.







»CL1:Wade:»CL0: Tell me about your accomplices:
      the graphics artists and
musicians behind your schemes. Do they
work for you or with you? 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: Not actually the way I want it. I
     get some graphics and musics. 
Then I sit, listen to the music, think
about gfx and code I have and that's 
where the design comes from. Then I
code a demo, change my plans during it
and... Next FLOPPY release. But it
shouldn't be that way. I want to
change it.






»CL1:Wade:»CL0: You mentioned design. Surely
      this should be an essential
ingredient in order for your plans to
succeed. Should a coder dedicate more
time on designing their production? 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: In Floppy, when Thorus was a
     member, I spent my time on coding
and he spent his time on design. Now,
I spend my time on coding, and the
rest (very small) on design. But I
guess the first place takes DESIGN,
and the second - CODING.





»CL1:Wade:»CL0: You seem to promote            »PIC:Darklight.+EC_13.iff»
      the Amiga scene, but
have you ever considered
using your talents to help
others? Providing them with
