»CL3:Zig:»CL2: I coded a long time
     ago, but never
released...

»CL1:Wade:»CL0: So, if you could
     improve the scene, how
would you do it?
»CL3:Zig:»CL2: Make the Amiga
     hardware cheaper. Then
many good Amiga-sceners, which bought PCs, would return.




















»CL1:Wade:»CL0: I too would like to see that
      happen. But, restrictions are a
fundamental part of the Amiga's
success. It's what drove sceners of
the past, the toils of working within
a 1mb limit and a couple of floppy
disks. One could appreciate their work
more, knowing the boundaries they had
managed to exceed. These days, there
are no limits and the coder has far
less  difficulty achieving his/her
goals. 

»CL9:<»CL1:Zig shakes his head disapprovingly»CL9:>»

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: I don't think so. Coders
     concentrate their abilities on
other stuff then. The new demos are
very professional programs which show
users the possibilities of the
machine. That's what most people want.
And memory (hardware) is not problem
now. So why not use it, if you can?
Can you imagine a demo written on
a1200 without turbo and fast-ram
nowadays?

»CL1:Wade:»CL0: Absolutely. If there were more
      standard AGA demos, I'm sure
many ex-sceners would have remained in
the scene. 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: For example. It's not possible to
     create c2p for 15bit truecolor
that will be faster than chip-writing
and preloading cache trick. So if i
got that speed, what is there to
speed-up? 


»CL1:Wade:»CL0: Take Sanity's Arte as an
      example. Even in this day and
age, it remains one of the greatest
demos the Amiga has ever seen, and it
only requires an A500 to run. 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: That's true. But would you like a
     demo like Arte released this
year?

»CL1:Wade:»CL0: Definitely. It would certainly
      motivate my scene activities.
The beauty of such demos is that they
are designed purely for the Amiga,
using it's custom hardware to the
full. It takes a pretty powerful PC to
emulate a demo such as Arte, whereas a
simple 486 could handle most Amiga
demos of today's era. 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: I don't think so. The times go by
     so the technique too. Better CPU
(hardware) doesn't change the coder
(man).

»CL1:Wade:»CL0: What about the challenge? Don't
      coders thrive on that any more?
One hardly needs much in the way of
low level coding expertise to program
a PPC demo. It's speed could make an
Amos demo look passable. 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: That's right, but it depends on
     what do you want to achieve. I
can't do anything more on 060 so I
bought PPC card and BVision. There are
some limits you can't beat. Especially
AGA and slow BUS.

»CL9:<»CL1:Wade sighs»CL9:>»

»CL1:Wade:»CL0: Have you ever stolen other
      people's work? I.e. source code
and routines. 

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: Never rip. I don't like using
     other people's sources. I write
my own sources few times, cause I
don't like to use old stuff. All my
demos might look similar, but the code
in each other is completely new or
updated.

»CL1:Wade:»CL0: Do you have any plans for the
      future?

»CL3:Zig:»CL2: Currently no, but I think about a
     demo for BVision. Maybe a version
for MC68060 and AGA too. But time will
show what I do.

    »PIC:Kempy.person_end_hires»


















